Access mapping

_w → Developer (project level)
_r → Reporter (project level)
gl-restricted-read → Reporter (group level)
gl-<product>-dev → Developer (group level)
Key Characteristics
Existing Bitbucket _r / _w LDAP groups are reused
Inner sourcing enabled via Restricted groups
Confidential projects have no inherited access
Projects may optionally be grouped with a defined Owner
Hybrid IAM: SSCAM + SailPoint
Consequences (Accepted)

✅ Fast migration
✅ Minimal disruption
✅ Immediate inner sourcing

⚠ Hybrid LDAP management
⚠ Partial GitLab inheritance usage
⚠ Not a final state

Approach 2 – Domain / Product‑Line Group‑Centric Model (Target State)
What it is

A fully GitLab‑native authorization model where access is structured around stable application domains or product lines, not individual repositories.

Visual – How It Looks in GitLab
GitLab
└── payments/                     (domain / product line)
    ├── api/
    │   ├── payments-api
    │   └── payments-batch
    ├── ui/
    │   └── payments-ui
    └── confidential/
        └── payments-secrets

Identity & Access Management
SailPoint (single IAM system)
├── gl-payments-read
├── gl-payments-dev
├── gl-payments-maint
└── gl-payments-owner


All access is assigned at GitLab group level and inherited

Key Characteristics
Domains defined using LeanIX, CI/controller grouping, ownership analysis
GitLab groups represent long‑lived responsibilities
SSH / CI / approval policies enforced once at group level
Single IAM model (SailPoint only)
Project‑specific groups largely eliminated
Consequences (Known)

✅ Strong governance & auditability
✅ Excellent scalability
✅ Full GitLab inheritance model

⚠ Upfront analysis required
⚠ Breaks direct _r / _w mapping
⚠ CI/CD ecosystem integration impacts
⚠ Higher transition effort

Side‑by‑Side Comparison
Dimension	Approach 1 – Hybrid	Approach 2 – Domain
Intended role	Transition	Target
Migration disruption	Low	High
Reuse Bitbucket groups	Yes	No
IAM systems	SSCAM + SailPoint	SailPoint only
GitLab inheritance	Partial	Full
Inner sourcing	Yes	Yes
Governance strength	Medium	High
Ecosystem impact	Low	High
Recommended Evolution Path
Onboard all projects using Approach 1
Introduce grouping and ownership incrementally
Validate domain structures and ownership
Migrate selected domains to Approach 2
Decommission project‑level _r / _w groups

Approach 1 enables progress without blocking.
Approach 2 is the destination once structure and ecosystem maturity are in place.




GitLab Grouping Criteria and Structure
Criteria for grouping applications

GitLab groups should be defined using stable application characteristics, not organisational ownership. The following criteria are recommended:

Deployment & exposure model (primary criterion)

Where the application is deployed
Live - Cloud Landing Zone
Live - Cloud SaaS
Live - Customer Premises
Live - Production
Live - Enterprise
Live - Public Web - SdC
Non-live - Cloud Landing Zone
Non-live - Enterprise
Who can access it
Examples: internal‑only, production network, customer‑deployed

Security and risk profile

Web‑facing vs non web‑facing
Deployment in restricted zones (e.g. pseudo‑com)
Need for additional security or approval controls

Compliance and reporting needs

Ability to report on all production apps
Ability to report on customer‑deployed software
Ability to scope audits and controls consistently

These criteria reflect what an application is, not who owns it, and therefore remain valid across organisational reworks.

Why grouping this way
Durability: deployment model and exposure change rarely, while teams change frequently
Policy inheritance: security, SoD, and CI/CD controls can be enforced once at group level
Auditability: enables native GitLab reporting without tags or manual classification
Consistency: avoids per‑project exceptions and configuration drift

This turns GitLab groups into a governance and control structure, not just a folder hierarchy.




